The Socialist Party of Nigeria (SPN) has warned Oyo State governor, Seyi Makinde against reopening of the state Secretariat for the civil servants to resume duty on April 20.  The party in a statement  made available to journalists in Ibadan by Comrade Ayodeji Adigun kicked against the planned reopening of the secretariat for civil servants in the state to resume work after fumigating and decontaminate it, saying the rising cases of coronavirus patients gives cause for concerns.  The party said, “SPN welcomes the plan to decontaminate the secretariat, even though we are worried that it could end up being another window to loot the public fund.  “However, we fault the decision by the state government to reopen the secretariat immediately after its decontamination as we believe that this will unnecessarily endanger the life of workers with the rising numbers of cases of COVID-19 in the state.  “Therefore, we demand from the leadership of NLC and TUC, in the state for a concrete response against this moves by the state government in order to ensure that the life and interest of mass of the workers in the state are adequately protected.” it said  The party added, “if workers can be asked to proceed on compulsory holiday when one case of COVID-19 was recorded in the state, saying “we strongly believed that it will be unthinkable and act of insensitivity if the same government should proceed with the plan to reopen the secretariat for workers to resumes now that the number of COVID-19 cases officially reported in the state has increased exponentially from one to eleven with likely cases of community transmission of the virus among the workers and the  poor in the state”,  SPN lamented the present situation of things in the state, saying a single diagnosing centre was available to test the cases of COVID-19 for a population of over six million people in the state.  “This is quite ridiculous and raises a huge doubt over the veracity of the huge amount of N1 billion the state government has so far claimed to have spent on its effort to curtail the spread of the virus in the state.  ”It is in the light of this unfortunate shortage of facilities for mass testing that, we welcome the government plan to establish additional two testing centres to increase the number in the state to three,’’ SPN said. 